output:
As I walked out on the streets of Laredo, As I walked out on Laredo one day,
I spied a young cowboy all wrapped in white linen,
Wrapped in white linen as cold as the clay.
I can see by your outfit that you are a cowboy,
These words he did say as I boldly walked by.
Come and sit down beside me and hear my sad story,
I was shot in the breast and I know I must die.
It was once in the saddle I used to go dashing,
Once in the saddle I used to go game.
First to the cart house and then down to Roses,
But I'm shot in the breast and I'm dying today.
Got six jolly cowboys to carry my coffin, Six dancehall maidens to bear up my paul,
Throw bunches of roses all over my coffin, Roses to deaden the clouds as they fall.
Then beat the drum slowly, play the fife lowly,
Leave the dead march as you carry me along, Take me to the green welly, leave the sod or me,
I'm a young cowboy and I know I must go on.
Then go write a letter to my great mother, And tell her the cowboy that she loved is gone,
But please not one word of the man who had killed me,
Don't mention his name, let his name we pass on.
And thus he had spoken, the hot sun was setting, The streets of Laredo grew cold as the clay,
We took the young cowboy down to the green welly, And there stands his marker we make to this day.
We beat the drum slowly, play the fife lowly, Leave the dead march as we carried him along,
Down to the green welly, leave the sod or him, He was a young cowboy and he said he done wrong.
